Executive summary

Demand is concentrated in the mid-priced catalog, with the $50–74 band performing best overall on volume. It generates 1,839 registrations, or 32.1% of all registrations, the highest of any price band. The next largest bands are $25–49 with 1,408 registrations (24.6%) and $75–99 with 1,183 registrations (20.6%). Together, the $25–99 range accounts for roughly 77% of total registrations, indicating that this is the core pricing zone for the program.

Fill rates are strongest in the upper-middle bands, not at the very lowest prices. The highest average fill rate comes from $75–99 at 82.1%, followed by $150+ at 76.6%, $50–74 at 76.3%, and $100–149 at 76.1%. Lower-priced classes lag behind, with $25–49 at 71.2% and especially under $25 at 60.8%. Sellout rates follow a similar pattern: they rise steadily with price, from 9.8% below $25 to 42.6% at $150+, suggesting that higher prices are not suppressing demand in the way one might expect.

Revenue is also led by the middle and upper-middle price bands. In total dollars, $50–74 generates the most revenue at $79,255, followed by $75–99 at $70,550, $150+ at $55,115, and $100–149 at $49,525. On a per-class basis, revenue climbs sharply as prices rise: average revenue per class is $90 for classes under $25, $259 for $25–49, $727 for $50–74, $775 for $75–99, $718 for $100–149, and $1,173 for $150+. That makes the highest-priced classes the most productive economically on a per-class basis, even though they represent a smaller share of total registrations.

The clearest signs of underpricing appear in the $75–99 and $150+ bands. The $75–99 band combines the highest fill rate (82.1%), a 40.7% sellout rate, and still shows a positive average waitlist (0.6), which suggests demand is strong even at that price point. The $150+ band is even more striking: despite being the most expensive, it still delivers a 76.6% fill rate, the highest sellout rate (42.6%), the highest average waitlist (1.1), and by far the highest revenue per class ($1,173). That pattern suggests at least some premium classes may still have pricing headroom. By contrast, the under-$25 band looks least efficient: it has the lowest fill rate, lowest sellout rate, low waitlist pressure, and very low revenue per class, which suggests low pricing alone is not enough to unlock strong demand.

There are fewer signs of true overpricing by price band overall, but some signals appear in the class-level scatter. A handful of very high-priced classes sit at modest fill rates, including some above $200–$300 that fill only around half capacity or lower, and an outlier near $450 that filled only about 25%. So while higher prices are not broadly hurting performance, the very top end likely becomes more sensitive and needs tighter calibration by offering type.

Performance clearly differs by subcategory. In Art, Fiber Arts, Science, and Storytelling, the trend lines suggest that higher-priced classes tend to fill as well or better than cheaper ones, implying room to price more confidently. Culinary appears relatively flat, suggesting demand is less price-sensitive within its observed range. In contrast, Outdoor Education and Wellness show negative price/fill relationships, where higher prices tend to correspond with lower fill rates, implying greater price sensitivity and less room for aggressive price expansion. That means pricing strategy should not be uniform across the catalog: some subcategories appear able to support higher price points, while others likely require tighter value-for-price discipline.

Overall, the pricing story is strong: the business performs best in the $50–99 range, premium classes can still work well when positioned correctly, and the biggest optimization opportunity is likely not broad discounting, but more targeted price calibration by subcategory and by the highest-demand premium offers.

Board-style summary

- The $50–74 band is the volume engine: it drives 1,839 registrations (32.1%) and the most total revenue ($79.3K).
- The $75–99 band is the strongest all-around price point: it has the highest fill rate (82.1%), strong sellout performance, and high revenue per class.
- Premium pricing is working: $150+ classes have the highest sellout rate (42.6%), highest waitlist (1.1), and highest revenue per class ($1,173), suggesting some premium offers may still have pricing headroom.
- Low prices are not automatically better: classes under $25 have the weakest fill, weakest sellout, and lowest revenue productivity.
- Pricing power varies by subcategory: Art, Fiber Arts, Science, and Storytelling appear more resilient to higher pricing, while Wellness and Outdoor Education look more price-sensitive.


